  "doc_id": "3639",
  "text": "Although the effectiveness of onabotulinumtoxinA for the treatment of NDO has been verified, the dose used in clinical practice remains controversial. Nuanthaisong U and colleagues reported that in patients with neurogenic bladder, over 360 U of onabotulinumtoxinA was an effective treatment [CITATION_1] . However, our review mainly focused on 200 or 300 U. In this study, the intradetrusor injection of onabotulinumtoxinA (300 or 200 U) had a significant therapeutic effect on NDO patients who were refractory to treatment with oral antimuscarinic drugs. Although the limited number of patients in this study set prevented us from drawing definite conclusions about efficacy and safety, our meta-analysis added new RCT articles based on the previous systematic review. Considering the discussed results, our study confirmed the results of previous studies regarding the beneficial effects of intradetrusor injection of onabotulinumtoxinA in patients with NDO.",
